Student 1: System Architecture & Platform Administration
Role: The Architect.

Git Branch Name: feature/platform-foundation

Primary Actor (from IS498): Admin & System Stakeholders.

Detailed Tasks (Checklist):

Unified Authentication System:

Develop a Sign-Up/Sign-In portal that routes users based on their role:

Customer: Redirects to the Storefront.

Store Owner: Redirects to the Store Dashboard.

Admin: Redirects to the Platform Administration Console.

Implement RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) middleware to secure routes (e.g., ensuring a Customer cannot access Store Owner settings).

Implement Password Hashing security measures as specified in the "Security Impact" section.

Platform Admin Dashboard:

Create a view for the Admin to oversee all registered Stores.

Implement "Suspend Store" functionality (changing Store.status to 'Inactive').

Create a "User Management" table to view all registered Store Owners and Customers.

Subscription Management:

Implement the logic for Store Owners to select a PlanType (Basic/Premium) during registration, linking to the Subscription entity.

âš¡ How to start immediately: Use dummy data for users. Do not wait for the UI to be perfect; focus on the logic.

Student 2: Store Owner Dashboard & Catalog Management
Role: The Core Builder.

Git Branch Name: feature/store-owner-dashboard

Primary Actor (from IS498): Store Owner & Store Admin.

Detailed Tasks (Checklist):

Store Configuration:

Develop the Store Owner profile settings (First Name, Last Name, Phone).

Create the Store Settings page to manage: Store Name, Domain Name, and Store Status.

Implement Store Admin management (allowing a Store Owner to add staff).

Product Management (CRUD):

Create: Interface to add new products to the Product table (Name, Title, Price).

Update: functionality to edit Product details and ProductOption (e.g., StockQty, AdditionalPrice).

Delete: Logic to archive products (change Product.status to 'Archived' instead of deleting).

Inventory & Variants:

Build a UI for managing ProductOptions (defining OptionName like "Size" and OptionValue like "Large").

Display "Low Stock" alerts for the Store Owner.

âš¡ How to start immediately: Hardcode a store_id = 1 in your code. Assume the Store Owner is already logged in.

Student 3: Customer Storefront & Shopping Experience
Role: The Frontend Specialist.

Git Branch Name: feature/customer-storefront

Primary Actor (from IS498): Customer.

Detailed Tasks (Checklist):

Public Store Interface:

Develop the Home Page that renders dynamically based on the Store.DomainName or ID.

Display a grid of active Products with their Price and Title.

Implement Search and Filtering functionality.

Product Discovery:

Product Details Page: Show full product information, including images and ProductOption selection (Size/Color).

Reviews System: Display Review.Rating and Review.Comment for the product.

Shopping Cart System:

Implement the Cart logic:

Add item to CartItem.

Update Quantity.

Calculate Subtotal and TotalPrice dynamically.

Create a Cart Drawer or Page for the Customer to review items before checkout.

âš¡ How to start immediately: Create a mock_products.json file with fake data. Build the entire UI using this file. Once Student 2 finishes the API, switch the mock file with the real API URL.

Student 4: Order Fulfillment & Operations
Role: The Operations Manager.

Git Branch Name: feature/orders-operations

Primary Actor (from IS498): Customer (for Checkout) & Store Owner (for Fulfillment).

Detailed Tasks (Checklist):

Checkout & Payment:

Develop the Checkout Page where the Customer inputs ShippingAddress and ShippingPhone.

Implement the Payment interface to select Payment.Method and generate a Payment.ProviderRef.

Transaction: Logic to convert a Cart into a confirmed Order and clear the cart.

Order Management (Store Owner View):

Dashboard view for Store Owners to see incoming Orders.

Functionality to update Order.Status (Pending -> Processing -> Shipped).

Shipment Tracking:

Interface to generate a Shipment record with a TrackingNumber.

Customer view to track their ShipmentStatus and DeliveredAt date.

Reporting:

Simple analytics for the Store Owner showing TotalAmount of sales.

âš¡ How to start immediately: Create a fake "Cart Object" in your code. Build the Checkout process assuming the cart is full. Do not wait for Student 3 to finish the "Add to Cart" button.
